SIMPLE: transom
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Transom
<hw>Tran"som</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Probably fr. L.
<ets>transtrum</ets> a crossbeam, transom, from <ets>trans</ets> across.
Cf. <er>Trestle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A
horizontal crossbar in a window, over a door, or between a door and a
window above it. <xex>Transom</xex> is the horizontal, as
<xex>mullion</xex> is the vertical, bar across an opening. See
<xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Mullion</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>One of the principal transverse
timbers of the stern, bolted to the sternpost and giving shape to the
stern structure; -- called also
<altname>transsummer</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Gun.)</fld> <def>The piece of wood or iron
connecting the cheeks of some gun carriages.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>The vane of a cross-staff.</def>
<rj><au>Chambers.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Railroad)</fld> <def>One of the crossbeams
connecting the side frames of a truck with each other.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Transom knees</b></col> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld>,
<cd>knees bolted to the transoms and after timbers.</cd> --
<col><b>Transom window</b></col>. <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A
window divided horizontally by a transom or transoms.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>A window over a door, with a transom between.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Transpadane</ent>⟦br⟧
